The 'requires an index' error means Firestore can't execute your query using single-field indexes — it needs a composite index that covers the exact combination of fields you're filtering and sorting on.

**Your Query Pattern:**
```javascript
query(
  collection(db, 'tracks'),
  where('artistId', '==', artistId),
  where('status', '==', 'released'),
  orderBy('releaseDate', 'desc'),
  limit(25)
)
```

**Required Composite Index:**
```json
// firestore.indexes.json
{
  "indexes": [
    {
      "collectionGroup": "tracks",
      "queryScope": "COLLECTION",
      "fields": [
        { "fieldPath": "artistId", "order": "ASCENDING" },
        { "fieldPath": "status", "order": "ASCENDING" },
        { "fieldPath": "releaseDate", "order": "DESCENDING" }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

**Rule:** The index must match (1) all equality filters, (2) all range filters, (3) the orderBy field, in that exact order. The sort direction of the orderBy must match the index field direction.

**Deployment:**
```bash
firebase deploy --only firestore:indexes
```
Index building takes 2–10 minutes depending on collection size.

**Pagination Setup (cursor-based, not offset):**
```javascript
// First page
const q = query(collection(db, 'tracks'), where('artistId', '==', id), where('status', '==', 'released'), orderBy('releaseDate', 'desc'), limit(25));
const snapshot = await getDocs(q);
const lastDoc = snapshot.docs[snapshot.docs.length - 1];

// Next page
const q2 = query(..., startAfter(lastDoc), limit(25));
```
Never use offset-based pagination with Firestore — it reads all skipped documents and charges for them.
